#compdef starkscan
# =============================================================================
# starkscan — Starkscan Contract Verifier.  Submits Cairo (StarkNet's smart-
#             contract language) source code to Starkscan's verification
#             service so a deployed contract's class hash + source code
#             become publicly verifiable on the Starkscan block explorer
#             (the StarkNet equivalent of Etherscan).  Walks the developer
#             through an Inquirer-driven wizard: pick networks (mainnet /
#             testnet / sepolia), select source files from a fuzzy-path
#             picker, choose entry-point class, and submit; an ora-driven
#             spinner shows job-progress while Starkscan's backend
#             verifies the source against the on-chain bytecode.
#             Essential for StarkNet projects shipping contracts that
#             need user-trustable provenance — without verification,
#             users have no way to confirm a deployed contract's source
#             code matches what the developer claims.
#
# Author:  Starkscan team (starkscan organization — block-explorer service
#          for StarkNet, similar to Etherscan/Polygonscan/BscScan but
#          for the StarkNet L2 rollup)
# Source:  https://github.com/starkscan/starkscan-verifier
# CLI:     src/verifyClass.ts (uses inquirer for prompts + ora for
#                              spinner during verification submission)
# Library: sindresorhus/ora
#          ("Elegant terminal spinner" — Sindre Sorhus's canonical
#           JS spinner library, the JS-side equivalent of Rust's
#           indicatif R522 and Go's cheggaaa/pb R523)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 1264+ stars on starkscan/starkscan-verifier;
#          ora itself is 9710+ stars and the most-deployed JS
#          spinner library across npm.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 38
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 38TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 37 to 38 documented libraries (sindresorhus/ora via starkscan).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=38, Go=38, TypeScript-Node=38 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 38
# RESTORED — fifth three-way tie of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now
# spans 263 cross-language CLI library variants across 63 documented
# languages.
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE PROGRESS-LIBRARY TRIPLE for the top three
# languages in the taxonomy:
#   * R522: Rust    → console-rs/indicatif (2016 — Rust progress canonical)
#   * R523: Go      → cheggaaa/pb          (2014 — Go progress canonical)
#   * R524: TS-Node → sindresorhus/ora     (2015 — JS spinner canonical)
# All three are CANONICAL PROGRESS-AXIS libraries for their ecosystems,
# released within ~2 years of each other (2014-2016).  Where prompts have
# multi-library competition (dialoguer/inquire/cliclack in Rust; survey/huh
# in Go; Inquirer.js/prompts/Clack in JS), progress reporting has TIGHTER
# library winners — ora in JS, indicatif in Rust, cheggaaa/pb in Go all
# enjoy near-monopoly status in their language ecosystems.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS sindresorhus/ora AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 38TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# sindresorhus/ora (https://github.com/sindresorhus/ora, 9710+ stars) is
# **Sindre Sorhus's "elegant terminal spinner"** — the CANONICAL and
# most-deployed JS spinner library.  Released in 2015 by Sindre Sorhus
# (also author of meow R516 + 1800+ other npm packages), ora is the
# JS-ecosystem equivalent of Rust's indicatif R522 and Go's cheggaaa/pb
# R523.  Used by npm itself (npm install spinner), yarn, pnpm,
# vite/vitest startup spinners, nuxt-cli, npx itself, hundreds of
# create-X scaffolders, and thousands of CLIs that need a "loading..."
# indicator.
#
# Note: ora is SPINNER-focused (not full progress bars).  The JS
# ecosystem has separate libraries for known-length progress bars
# (cli-progress, progress, gauge), while ora dominates the spinner
# (unknown-length task) niche.  This is different from indicatif R522
# and cheggaaa/pb R523 which cover BOTH bars + spinners in a single
# library — JS has split the concerns into separate libraries.
#
# ora is DISTINCT from every documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. SPINNER-FIRST DESIGN (NOT FULL PROGRESS BARS) — ora is
#      the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library whose primary concern
#      is SPINNER DISPLAY rather than argv parsing or interactive
#      prompts.  Compare:
#         commander/yargs/cac (R508)/...: argv parsers
#         @inquirer/prompts R520:        interactive prompts
#         @clack/prompts R512:           interactive prompts + spinner
#                                         unified
#         meow R516:                     argv parser
#         ora (THIS):                    SPINNER-only (separate from
#                                         argv parsers AND prompts)
#      Where Rust's indicatif R522 and Go's cheggaaa/pb R523 combine
#      progress bars + spinners in one library, **ora is JS's
#      spinner-only specialist**.  Sister libraries handle bars:
#        cli-progress  — JS progress bars (cli-progress 1300+ stars)
#        progress      — JS progress bars (older — 1900+ stars)
#        gauge         — npm-bundled progress (used by npm CLI itself)
#      **First documented TS-Node CLI library whose primary concern is
#      SPINNER DISPLAY rather than argv parsing or prompts.**
#
#   2. 80+ NAMED SPINNER STYLES VIA cli-spinners SIBLING — ora's
#      spinner FRAMES are loaded from sindresorhus/cli-spinners — a
#      separate npm package that ships **80+ pre-defined spinner
#      styles** as JSON:
#         dots             ⠋ ⠙ ⠹ ⠸ ⠼ ⠴ ⠦ ⠧ ⠇ ⠏
#         dots2            ⣾ ⣽ ⣻ ⢿ ⡿ ⣟ ⣯ ⣷
#         line             - \ | /
#         pipe             ┤ ┘ ┴ └ ├ ┌ ┬ ┐
#         simpleDots       .  .. ...
#         star             ✶ ✸ ✹ ✺ ✹ ✷
#         star2            + x * (centered tinier star)
#         flip             _ _ _ - ` ` ' ´ - _ _ _
#         hamburger        ☱ ☲ ☴
#         growVertical     ▁ ▃ ▄ ▅ ▆ ▇ ▆ ▅ ▄ ▃
#         growHorizontal   ▏ ▎ ▍ ▌ ▋ ▊ ▉ ▊ ▋ ▌ ▍ ▎
#         balloon          .  o  O  @  *  (cycle)
#         balloon2         .  o  O  °  O  o  .
#         noise            ▓ ▒ ░
#         bouncingBar      [    ] [=   ] [==  ] [=== ]
#         bouncingBall     ( ●    ) (  ●   ) ...
#         smiley           😄 😝
#         monkey           🙈 🙈 🙉 🙊
#         hearts           💛 💙 💜 💚 ❤️
#         clock            🕛 🕐 🕑 🕒 ...
#         earth            🌍 🌎 🌏
#         moon             🌑 🌒 🌓 🌔 🌕 🌖 🌗 🌘
#         runner           🚶 🏃
#         pong             ▐⠂       ▌ ▐⠈       ▌ ...
#         shark            ▐|\____________▌ ▐_|\___________▌
#         dqpb             d q p b
#         weather          ☀️ ☀️ ☀️ 🌤 ⛅️ 🌥 ☁️ 🌧
#         christmas        🌲 🎄
#         grenade          ، ’ ` ‘ . ⌣ ◌ ⊙ ๏ Ϙ © ʘ ʘ ʘ ʘ
#         point            ∙∙∙ ●∙∙ ∙●∙ ∙∙● ∙∙∙
#         layer            - = ≡
#         betaWave         ρββββββ ββρβββββ βββρββββ ...
#         ... and ~40 more
#
#      cli-spinners is its OWN npm package — used by ora but also
#      by many other JS CLI tools that want spinner frames without
#      the full ora rendering.  Compare:
#        indicatif R522:    one default spinner + caller-customizable
#                            via ProgressStyle template strings
#        cheggaaa/pb R523:  one spinner + custom-template registration
#        @clack/prompts:    one spinner style, fixed
#        ora:               80+ pre-defined spinner styles via
#                            cli-spinners package — the widest
#                            spinner-aesthetic library across
#                            documented progress libraries.
#      **First documented progress/spinner library with a separate
#      sibling package providing 80+ named spinner-frame definitions.**
#
#   3. ESM-ONLY SINCE v6 (PARALLEL TO meow R516) — ora 6.x+ is
#      ESM-ONLY, matching Sindre Sorhus's broader push to deprecate
#      CommonJS across his package ecosystem:
#         import ora from "ora";        // ESM-only since ora 6
#      Compare:
#        indicatif R522 (Rust):  N/A (Rust crates don't have JS-style
#                                 ESM/CJS split)
#        cheggaaa/pb R523 (Go):  N/A
#        meow R516 (TS-Node):    ESM-only since v10
#        @clack/prompts R512:    ESM-only
#        Inquirer.js v9 R520:    ESM-only
#        ora:                    ESM-ONLY since v6 — matches Sindre's
#                                  broader ESM-first ecosystem stance.
#      Reflects Sindre's leadership in pushing the JS ecosystem to
#      ESM-only — ora's ESM-only transition happened alongside meow's
#      and many other Sindre packages' transitions.
#
#   4. CHAINABLE TERMINAL-STATE METHODS (.start / .succeed / .fail /
#      .warn / .info / .stopAndPersist) — ora's API exposes specific
#      methods for the common "spinner outcome" patterns:
#         const spinner = ora("Loading data...").start();
#         try {
#             await fetchData();
#             spinner.succeed("Data loaded");   // ✔ Data loaded
#         } catch (err) {
#             spinner.fail("Failed");           // ✖ Failed
#         }
#
#         // Other terminal states:
#         spinner.warn("Cache miss");          // ⚠ Cache miss
#         spinner.info("Using fallback");       // ℹ Using fallback
#         spinner.stopAndPersist({
#             symbol: "✓",
#             text:   "Custom finished state"
#         });
#      Each terminal-state method:
#        - Stops the spinner animation
#        - Replaces the spinner glyph with the symbol (✔ / ✖ / ⚠ / ℹ)
#        - Optionally updates the text
#        - Returns the spinner for further chaining
#      Compare:
#        indicatif R522:    finish() / finish_with_message() /
#                            finish_and_clear() / abandon() —
#                            simpler terminal-state vocabulary
#        cheggaaa/pb R523:  Finish() / Abort() — minimal
#        @clack/prompts:    spinner.stop(message) — single terminal
#        ora:               .succeed() / .fail() / .warn() / .info()
#                            / .stopAndPersist() — FIVE NAMED
#                            terminal states with semantic glyphs.
#      The semantic-glyph terminal-state vocabulary is ora's signature
#      design — copied by many JS spinner libraries since.
#
#   5. `oraPromise()` ASYNC WRAPPING UTILITY — ora exports an
#      `oraPromise()` helper that wraps any Promise with a spinner:
#         import { oraPromise } from "ora";
#
#         const data = await oraPromise(
#             fetch("https://api.example.com/data"),
#             {
#                 text: "Fetching data...",
#                 successText: "Data fetched",
#                 failText:    "Failed to fetch data",
#             }
#         );
#         // Spinner shows during the Promise, then automatically
#         // resolves to success or fail based on Promise outcome.
#      Compare:
#        indicatif R522:    no Promise-wrapping (Rust uses async/await
#                            differently; indicatif wraps iterators
#                            via .progress())
#        cheggaaa/pb R523:  no goroutine-wrapping (Go uses channels;
#                            pb wraps io.Reader/io.Writer instead)
#        @clack/prompts:    spinner.start/stop must be called manually
#                            around the awaited Promise
#        ora:               oraPromise(promise, options) — UNIQUE
#                            Promise-automatic-spinner wrapping in
#                            the spinner-library space.
#      Reflects the Promise-centric nature of modern JS — ora's
#      oraPromise composes naturally with await.
#
# Bonus: ora has **`.suffixText`** for static text rendered AFTER the
# main spinner text — useful for showing "currently downloading X..."
# without rewriting the prefix each tick.  And **`.indent`** for
# nested spinner indentation in TUI scenarios.  And **`.discardStdin`**
# for preventing input from interfering with the rendered spinner.
#
# THE sindresorhus/ora API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   import ora, { oraPromise, spinners } from "ora";
#
#   // Basic spinner:
#   const spinner = ora("Loading data...").start();
#   await doWork();
#   spinner.succeed("Data loaded!");
#
#   // With custom spinner style + color + indent:
#   const spinner = ora({
#       text:    "Searching",
#       spinner: "dots12",       // one of 80+ named styles
#       color:   "magenta",
#       indent:  2,
#   }).start();
#
#   // Update text mid-spin:
#   spinner.text = "Still searching...";
#   spinner.color = "yellow";
#
#   // Terminal states (each stops the spinner):
#   spinner.succeed("Done!");                              // ✔ Done!
#   spinner.fail("Failed!");                                // ✖ Failed!
#   spinner.warn("Cache miss");                             // ⚠ Cache miss
#   spinner.info("Fallback");                               // ℹ Fallback
#   spinner.stopAndPersist({ symbol: "✓", text: "Custom" });
#   spinner.stop();                                         // No symbol
#
#   // Promise-wrapping helper:
#   const result = await oraPromise(fetch(url), {
#       text:        "Fetching...",
#       successText: "Fetched",
#       failText:    "Fetch failed",
#   });
#
#   // Use spinners catalog separately:
#   import { spinners } from "cli-spinners";
#   console.log(spinners.dots);  // { interval: 80, frames: [...] }
#
# Spinner instance properties:
#   text, prefixText, suffixText  // text shown around spinner glyph
#   color                         // spinner glyph color (chalk style)
#   spinner                       // named spinner or custom { frames, interval }
#   indent                        // left-indent for nested TUIs
#   isSpinning                    // current animation state
#   interval                      // tick rate (ms; default from spinner style)
#   stream                        // output stream (default: process.stderr)
#   discardStdin                  // prevent stdin from interfering
#
# Spinner instance methods:
#   start([text])                 // begin animation
#   stop()                        // pause without symbol
#   succeed([text]) / fail([text]) / warn([text]) / info([text])
#   stopAndPersist({ symbol, prefixText, text, suffixText })
#   clear()                       // wipe current line, keep animation state
#   render()                      // force a frame render now
#   frame()                       // get next animation frame as string
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander           — chained .command().option().action() parser
#   * yargs               — chained .command(spec).demand().argv parser
#   * oclif               — file-based + class-per-command framework
#   * citty (UnJS)        — defineCommand({meta, args, run}) parser
#   * cac (R508)          — zero-dep single-file 4-API parser
#   * meow (R516)         — help-text-as-primary-input parser
#   * minimist            — pure parser, no command abstraction
#   * sade                — chained lightweight parser
#   * arg (Vercel)        — pure parser
#   * mri (lukeed)        — minimist replacement
#   * yargs-parser        — parsing kernel
#   * arg-parser          — typed plain object schema
#   * cleye R472          — string-command map + typed flags
#   * clipanion           — class-based with attribute decorators
#   * gluegun             — extension-plugin architecture
#   * stricli R484        — Bloomberg complex CLI framework
#   * type-flag           — low-level typed flag primitive
#   * tinyargs            — egoist's parser + Option class
#   * breadc              — modern minimal TS framework
#   * clerc R496          — plugin-driven typed chained API
#   * brocli R500         — factory-fn + method-chain + plain object
#   * command-line-args   — 75lb's three-stage parser
#   * cliffy (Deno-first) — chained + Promise-returning .parse()
#   * gunshi R504         — universal-runtime + i18n + 3 renderers
#   * @clack/prompts R512 — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT modern aesthetic
#                            (Clack — 2022) + unified spinner+progress
#   * @inquirer/prompts R520 — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT 2012 grandfather
#                                of all prompt libraries
#   * ora (THIS)          — SPINNER-FIRST library (canonical JS
#                            spinner — 9710-star ora by Sindre Sorhus
#                            + cli-spinners sibling with 80+ named
#                            spinner styles + ESM-only since v6 +
#                            chainable terminal-state methods
#                            .succeed/.fail/.warn/.info/.stopAndPersist
#                            + oraPromise() async wrapping helper)
#
# ora occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **CANONICAL JS SPINNER library**.
# The JS-side equivalent of Rust's indicatif R522 and Go's cheggaaa/pb
# R523 — but specifically the SPINNER half (JS splits bars + spinners
# into separate libraries).  The three together (indicatif / pb / ora)
# represent the canonical progress-axis libraries across the three top
# languages, all 2014-2016 vintage, all dominant in their ecosystems.
#
# REAL-WORLD sindresorhus/ora USERS:
#
#   * npm/cli itself — npm uses ora for installation progress
#   * yarn, pnpm — Yarn and pnpm both use ora-style spinners
#       (yarn has its own fork; pnpm uses ora directly)
#   * vitejs/vite — Vite's startup banner spinner
#   * vitest-dev/vitest — Vitest's test-discovery spinner
#   * nuxt/nuxt-cli — Nuxt's project scaffolder
#   * starkscan/starkscan-verifier (THIS, 1264*) — Cairo contract
#       verifier for StarkNet
#   * Hundreds of create-* scaffolders (create-next-app, create-vue,
#       create-svelte before Clack, etc.)
#   * Thousands of cobra-of-JS commander-based CLIs that need
#       "Loading..." indicators during async work
#   * Many Sindre Sorhus own packages: np (npm publish), gulp-changed,
#       imagemin-cli, sort-package-json, is-online-cli — all use ora
#       internally where appropriate
#
# ora's adoption pattern: **THE DEFAULT JS spinner library since 2015**.
# Has no real competitor in the spinner niche; alternatives like nanospinner
# or @phc/ora are deliberately marketed as "lighter than ora" — proving
# ora's dominance.  The 9710 stars are concentrated in Sindre Sorhus's
# broader ecosystem influence.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STARKSCAN'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/verifyClass.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   starkscan
#
# starkscan takes NO command-line arguments by default.  When launched,
# it walks the user through a verification wizard via Inquirer prompts
# + ora spinner during the verification submission:
#
#   1. NETWORK selection (inquirer multi-select):
#      - mainnet     — StarkNet mainnet (production contracts)
#      - testnet     — StarkNet testnet
#      - sepolia     — StarkNet sepolia testnet
#      - integration — StarkNet integration testnet
#
#   2. SOURCE FILES selection (inquirer-fuzzy-path picker):
#      Browse the project's Cairo source tree and select files to
#      submit.  Includes auto-detection of Scarb.toml / Cairo.toml
#      project layout.
#
#   3. ENTRY-POINT CLASS selection (inquirer search-list):
#      For multi-class Cairo source, pick which class is the
#      verifiable entry point (other classes are dependencies).
#
#   4. JOB SUBMISSION (ora spinner):
#      The selected source is bundled and POSTed to Starkscan's
#      verification API.  ora spinner shows "Submitting..." then
#      cycles through "Verifying..." states as Starkscan's backend
#      compiles + hashes + compares against on-chain bytecode.
#
#   5. RESULT DISPLAY (ora.succeed or ora.fail):
#      Success: prints the Starkscan class URL where the verified
#      source is now publicly viewable.
#      Failure: prints the verification error (mismatched bytecode,
#      unsupported Cairo version, missing dependency, etc.)
#
# Configuration:
#   Reads `.starkscan.toml` from cwd if present (default network,
#   default class identifier, etc.).
#
# Workflow:
#   $ cd my-starknet-project
#   $ starkscan                              # interactive wizard
#   # ... select networks, pick source files, choose entry-point class
#   ✔ Submitted to mainnet (job: abc123)
#   ✔ Verified on mainnet: https://starkscan.co/class/0x...
#
# StarkNet ecosystem context:
#   Cairo is StarkNet's smart-contract language (corpus has _cairo-*
#   completions for cairo-compile, cairo-execute, cairo-format,
#   cairo-run, cairo-test, sierra-compile, starknet-compile, etc.).
#   Starkscan is the block explorer; starkscan-verifier (THIS) is the
#   CLI for submitting source for public verification.  Sister
#   verifier tools: voyager-verifier (Voyager explorer), starknet-
#   foundry's `sncast` verify command (Foundry-style verification).
#
# =============================================================================

_starkscan() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    # starkscan is fully interactive — no CLI args.
    # Provide default file completion in case a user passes a path.
    _arguments -C \
        '*: :_files -g "*.(cairo|toml)"' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_starkscan "$@"
